fields.description:
AWS has introduced a simpler way to manipulate strings. We should support this simpler fn::Sub approach so we are compatible with templates that use it.

{quote}
Many CloudFormation templates perform some intricate string manipulation in order to construct command lines, file paths, and other values that cannot be fully determined until the stack is created.  Until now, this required the use of fn::Join. In combination with the JSON syntax, this results in some messy templates that were hard to understand and maintain. In order to simplify this important aspect of template development, we are introducing a new substitution function, fn::Sub. This function replaces variables (denoted by the syntax ${variable_name}) with their evaluated values.
{quote}

https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/aws-cloudformation-update-yaml-cross-stack-references-simplified-substitution/

comments.body:
Here is a template that demonstrates most of the "success" cases:
{code}
{
  "Parameters" : {
    "Param1" : {
      "Type" : "String"
    },
    "ImageId" : {
      "Type" : "String"
    }
  },
  "Resources" : {
    "Instance1" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : { "Fn::Sub" : "${ImageId}" }
      }
    },
    "SecurityGroup1" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup",
      "Properties" : {
        "GroupDescription" : {"Fn::Sub" : "InstanceId: ${Instance1}, Param1:${Param1}"}
      }
    },
    "SecurityGroup2" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup",
      "Properties" : {
        "GroupDescription" : {"Fn::Sub" : ["InstanceId.AvailabilityZone: ${Instance1.AvailabilityZone}, Param1:${Param1}, ImageId:${ImageId}", {"Param1" : "Param1Override"}]}
      }
    }
  },
  "Outputs" : {
    "Output1" : {
      "Value" : {"Fn::Sub" : ["AccountId:${AWS::AccountId} Literal: ${!ImageId} ImageId:${ImageId}", {"ImageId" : {"Fn::Join" : ["",["Over","ride"]]}}]}
    }
  }
}

{code}

You need to pass some value for Param1 and an ImageId.

outputs from
{code}euform-describe-stacks{code} look like
{code}[root@b-02 ~]# euform-describe-stacks
STACK	mystack	CREATE_COMPLETE			2016-11-02T05:21:47.888Z
PARAMETER	Param1		param1
PARAMETER	ImageId		emi-835edf14
OUTPUT	Output1	AccountId:000753394612 Literal: ${ImageId} ImageId:Override
{code}

and {code}euca-describe-groups{code}
look like
{code}[root@b-02 ~]# euca-describe-groups
GROUP	sg-55d555b6	000753394612	mystack-SecurityGroup1-FNLQWO89BMYW4	InstanceId: i-ed80a1c8, Param1:param1	
TAG	security-group	sg-55d555b6	aws:cloudformation:logical-id	SecurityGroup1
TAG	security-group	sg-55d555b6	aws:cloudformation:stack-id	arn:aws:cloudformation::000753394612:stack/mystack/6481e471-72b0-4dac-bd4c-5e48f13f3ef8
TAG	security-group	sg-55d555b6	aws:cloudformation:stack-name	mystack
GROUP	sg-9ead3673	000753394612	default	default group	
GROUP	sg-861ed8e7	000753394612	mystack-SecurityGroup2-GNGRUYKH6JZBH	InstanceId.AvailabilityZone: one, Param1:Param1Override, ImageId:emi-835edf14	
TAG	security-group	sg-861ed8e7	aws:cloudformation:logical-id	SecurityGroup2
TAG	security-group	sg-861ed8e7	aws:cloudformation:stack-id	arn:aws:cloudformation::000753394612:stack/mystack/6481e471-72b0-4dac-bd4c-5e48f13f3ef8
TAG	security-group	sg-861ed8e7	aws:cloudformation:stack-name	mystack{code}


Note:  AWS has some very good pre-launch type checking.  If you pass in {"Fn::GetAtt" : ["X","Y"]} for a resource X whose attribute Y is a list, for example, as one of the values in the mapping field for Fn::Sub, which requires either strings or functions that return strings, AWS will fail immediately.  We will not fail until the "Fn::Sub" function is evaluated, which is during the creation process.  We do some checking at pre-launch time, such as if {"Fn::GetAZs" : ""} was used in that place, but to check everything pre-launch would be prohibitive.
